  "prompt": "Does it hurt to get stitches?",
  "response": "Getting stitches can cause some discomfort, but the level of pain varies depending on several factors:\n\n1. Local anesthesia: Typically, before getting stitches, a healthcare provider will numb the area with a local anesthetic injection, which can cause a brief, sharp pinch.\n\n2. Wound location: Some areas are more sensitive than others, which can affect pain levels.\n\n3. Depth and size of the wound: Deeper or larger wounds may be more painful.\n\n4. Individual pain tolerance: People experience pain differently.\n\nGenerally, the numbing medication helps minimize pain during the stitching process. After the anesthesia wears off, you may experience:\n- Mild to moderate soreness\n- Stinging or burning sensation\n- Tenderness around the wound\n\nThe actual stitching process itself is usually not very painful due to the local anesthetic. Your healthcare provider can help manage any discomfort and provide pain management advice.",
